448
00:27:25,140 --> 00:27:29,720
Computational abstraction, what we've been praising this whole time, is about making the world useful.

449
00:27:30,500 --> 00:27:33,900
You strip away the details of the tree to calculate its lumber yield.

450
00:27:34,340 --> 00:27:37,400
You strip away the details of the driver to design the traffic system.

451
00:27:37,700 --> 00:27:40,300
You make the map smaller than the territory so you can use it.

452
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:40,560
Right.

453
00:27:40,940 --> 00:27:41,340
Useful.

454
00:27:41,900 --> 00:27:42,300
Efficient.

455
00:27:42,920 --> 00:27:44,560
Phenomenological reduction is the opposite.

456
00:27:45,160 --> 00:27:48,040
It's what philosophers like Husserl and Heidegger talked about.

457
00:27:48,040 --> 00:27:52,220
It's about stripping away your assumptions to see the world as it truly is.

458
00:27:52,620 --> 00:27:54,140
So it's not about making the map smaller.

459
00:27:54,320 --> 00:27:56,000
No, it's about making the map bigger.

460
00:27:56,360 --> 00:28:04,540
It's about seeing the tree not as lumber, but as a living, breathing, complex entity with roots and fungi and a place in an ecosystem.

461
00:28:04,920 --> 00:28:10,020
So one makes the world simple and you could say dead, and the other makes the world complex and alive.

462
00:28:10,380 --> 00:28:10,760
Exactly.

463
00:28:10,760 --> 00:28:16,060
And the dark genealogy the source warns about is what happens when we use computational abstraction on people.

464
00:28:16,440 --> 00:28:17,680
The bureaucratic fallacy.

465
00:28:18,040 --> 00:28:19,800
Reducing a human being to a number.

466
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:20,880
A statistic.

467
00:28:21,460 --> 00:28:22,520
It's more than just a number.

468
00:28:22,680 --> 00:28:23,640
It's a functional reduction.

469
00:28:24,380 --> 00:28:26,700
The source uses the image of the broken back.

470
00:28:27,060 --> 00:28:28,160
Yeah, that was visceral.

471
00:28:28,380 --> 00:28:30,400
Imagine a pharaoh building a pyramid.

472
00:28:31,100 --> 00:28:33,520
To the pharaoh, the slave is an abstraction.

473
00:28:34,180 --> 00:28:35,780
The slave is a force unit.

474
00:28:36,340 --> 00:28:38,060
The interface is movestone.

475
00:28:38,060 --> 00:28:39,780
The implementation details.

476
00:28:39,780 --> 00:28:41,840
The slave's pain.

477
00:28:41,840 --> 00:28:42,720
Their family.

478
00:28:42,900 --> 00:28:45,200
Their snapped spine are hidden.

479
00:28:45,560 --> 00:28:46,820
They're irrelevant to the function.

480
00:28:47,020 --> 00:28:49,020
They are encapsulated, to use the coding term.

481
00:28:49,060 --> 00:28:49,800
They're encapsulated.

482
00:28:49,960 --> 00:28:51,840
And to the pharaoh, the system is working perfectly.

483
00:28:51,960 --> 00:28:52,880
The stone moved.

484
00:28:52,880 --> 00:28:54,460
The contract was satisfied.

485
00:28:54,680 --> 00:28:56,240
The normal form was achieved.

486
00:28:56,680 --> 00:28:59,760
But the reality is a broken human body.

487
00:29:00,120 --> 00:29:01,700
This is the danger of a clean interface.

488
00:29:01,860 --> 00:29:02,620
It hides the blood.

489
00:29:03,020 --> 00:29:04,080
It hides the dependencies.

490
00:29:04,540 --> 00:29:06,020
This is what the source calls extraction.

491
00:29:06,620 --> 00:29:11,520
Extraction is when you abstract a resource, like a forest, into a simple commodity like timber,

492
00:29:11,760 --> 00:29:14,660
and you delete the ecological web that keeps the forest alive.

493
00:29:14,780 --> 00:29:14,980
Right.

494
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:17,360
You ignore the soil, the fungi, the water cycle.

495
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:20,580
You extract the timber, and then the underlying reality collapses.

496
00:29:20,980 --> 00:29:21,860
The forest dies.

497
00:29:22,260 --> 00:29:27,380
Because you tried to run a get timber function on a system that was actually a live forest system.

498
00:29:28,020 --> 00:29:29,060
The abstraction lied.

499
00:29:29,280 --> 00:29:30,700
The abstraction was leaky.

500
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:32,340
It was a bad model.

501
00:29:32,340 --> 00:29:37,120
It didn't account for the interdependencies that allowed the timber to exist in the first place.

502
00:29:37,280 --> 00:29:38,580
So how do we fix this?

503
00:29:38,820 --> 00:29:41,000
We can't just stop abstracting.

504
00:29:41,300 --> 00:29:44,480
We can't process every atom of the universe individually.

505
00:29:44,780 --> 00:29:45,960
We need maps.

506
00:29:46,240 --> 00:29:47,080
We need models.

507
00:29:47,340 --> 00:29:47,680
We do.

508
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:49,780
And the source doesn't advocate for that.

509
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:52,260
Instead, it proposes an ethics of reduction.

510
00:29:52,800 --> 00:29:54,780
It calls for responsible interfaces.

511
00:29:55,220 --> 00:29:57,060
What does a responsible interface look like?

512
00:29:57,140 --> 00:29:59,320
It looks like an interface that remembers what it deleted.

513
00:29:59,320 --> 00:30:02,600
It stores a memory of the complexity it collapsed.

514
00:30:03,220 --> 00:30:07,300
And crucially, it allows the underlying reality to veto the abstraction.

515
00:30:07,500 --> 00:30:08,600
Give me an example of a veto.

516
00:30:08,860 --> 00:30:10,580
Think about an AI hiring system.

517
00:30:10,940 --> 00:30:13,000
It abstracts candidates into a set of scores.

518
00:30:13,200 --> 00:30:13,720
That's efficient.

519
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:14,940
But a veto would be.

520
00:30:15,340 --> 00:30:18,400
If the system notices that it's rejecting all female candidates,

521
00:30:18,820 --> 00:30:21,460
the underlying reality, the fact of discrimination,

522
00:30:22,040 --> 00:30:24,060
overrides the abstraction of efficiency.

523
00:30:24,440 --> 00:30:26,360
The territory says your map is wrong.

524
00:30:26,860 --> 00:30:27,380
Exactly.

525
00:30:27,380 --> 00:30:29,000
The territory gets to speak.

526
00:30:29,400 --> 00:30:30,760
You have to listen to the friction.

527
00:30:31,220 --> 00:30:33,580
If the engine is screaming, you don't just turn up the radio.

528
00:30:34,060 --> 00:30:34,960
You look under the hood.

529
00:30:35,680 --> 00:30:37,900
We have to be willing to break the abstraction

530
00:30:37,900 --> 00:30:40,360
and look at the mess when people are getting hurt.

531
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:42,920
That feels like the ultimate lesson here.

532
00:30:43,440 --> 00:30:47,160
Abstraction is a tool, a powerful one, but it's not a truth.

533
00:30:47,280 --> 00:30:48,360
It is a method of compression.

534
00:30:48,820 --> 00:30:50,360
It is not reality itself.

535
00:30:50,360 --> 00:30:52,560
We have covered a staggering amount of ground today.

536
00:30:53,420 --> 00:30:58,380
From the redexes of lambda calculus to the null states of NCL chips.

537
00:30:58,540 --> 00:31:01,100
From the kneading of dough in sphere pop space.

538
00:31:01,180 --> 00:31:03,420
To the five-dimensional physics of the soul.

539
00:31:03,600 --> 00:31:04,240
It's a lot.

540
00:31:04,460 --> 00:31:05,900
But I hope the listener sees the thread.

541
00:31:06,120 --> 00:31:06,920
It's all the same thing.

542
00:31:07,400 --> 00:31:08,320
The grand equivalence.

543
00:31:08,960 --> 00:31:12,700
Abstraction equals reduction equals evaluation equals energy minimization.

544
00:31:12,940 --> 00:31:14,260
We are reduction engines.

545
00:31:14,600 --> 00:31:15,420
That is what we are.

546
00:31:15,740 --> 00:31:19,380
We take the infinite noise of the universe and we collapse it into habitable order.

547
00:31:19,380 --> 00:31:22,480
We build a floor to stand on over an abyss of chaos.

548
00:31:22,800 --> 00:31:23,420
Beautifully put.

549
00:31:23,780 --> 00:31:26,040
But we have to remember that the floor is artificial.

550
00:31:26,700 --> 00:31:29,060
And sometimes we need to look through the cracks.

551
00:31:29,260 --> 00:31:29,580
We do.

552
00:31:29,840 --> 00:31:31,740
You always leave us with a thought to chew on.

553
00:31:31,880 --> 00:31:33,960
Something to, you know, keep us up at night.

554
00:31:34,320 --> 00:31:38,300
What does the 5D RSVP Ising model have for us?

555
00:31:38,540 --> 00:31:42,620
Well, let's combine the predictive self with the energy minimization of physics.

556
00:31:42,780 --> 00:31:42,980
Okay.

557
00:31:43,160 --> 00:31:46,280
We said that your self is just a model trying to minimize surprise.

558
00:31:46,280 --> 00:31:50,320
And we said that computation is just the universe naturally falling into a lower energy state.

559
00:31:50,940 --> 00:31:50,960
Okay.

560
00:31:51,380 --> 00:31:51,960
I'm following.

561
00:31:52,380 --> 00:31:56,600
So usually we think, I am thinking a thought.

562
00:31:56,900 --> 00:31:58,280
I am the agent.

563
00:31:58,580 --> 00:31:59,960
I am doing the work.

564
00:32:00,120 --> 00:32:00,260
Right.

565
00:32:00,380 --> 00:32:01,180
I am the thinker.

566
00:32:01,320 --> 00:32:10,140
But if your thought is just the universe relaxing, if it's just the inevitable slide of that 5D field into a lower energy valley, then are you thinking?

567
00:32:10,540 --> 00:32:13,840
Or are your thoughts just the sound the universe makes as it settles?

568
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:14,280
Whoa.

569
00:32:14,420 --> 00:32:20,620
Is you, your entire identity, just the specific geometric shape where the universe found the path of least resistance?

570
00:32:21,100 --> 00:32:23,240
Are you the sculptor or are you just the clay?

571
00:32:23,540 --> 00:32:26,280
Am I the thinker or am I just the place where the thinking happens?

572
00:32:26,640 --> 00:32:27,040
Exactly.

573
00:32:27,160 --> 00:32:27,400
I think.

574
00:32:27,520 --> 00:32:30,520
I think I need to go lie down and minimize my own energy state for a while.

575
00:32:30,640 --> 00:32:31,860
Go find your normal form.

576
00:32:32,200 --> 00:32:33,680
Thank you so much for this journey.

577
00:32:34,040 --> 00:32:35,520
It has been a true deep dive.

578
00:32:35,760 --> 00:32:38,300
To our listeners, good luck with your own reductions.

579
00:32:38,740 --> 00:32:39,560
We'll see you next time.

